   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0179.xml"/>Ebenezer
            Blackwell</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>Everton</placeName><lb/><date when="1759-03-02">March 2, 1759</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>When it is probable I may alter my judgement or practice, I am very willing to speak
            upon any head. But when I am clearly and fully fixed, then I do not speak, for it would
            be lost labour. For this reason I did not speak the other night, because I was fully
            fixed.</p>
         <p>My <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>wife</persName> picks my lock and
            steals my papers. Afterwards she says, &apos;You cannot trust me.&apos; I answer,
            &apos;I cannot, till you restore what you stole and promise to steal no more.&apos; She
            replies, &apos;I will burn them, or lodge them with another, on such terms.&apos; I
            answer nothing. Do you ask why so? I answer to <hi rend="italic">you</hi>: 1) I will not
               <hi rend="italic">consent</hi> my goods shall be <hi rend="italic">burnt</hi>, much
            less accept it as a favour. I require her to <hi rend="italic">restore</hi> them. 2) I
            will not thank her for lodging them with another. I require that they be restored to <hi
               rend="italic">me</hi>. 3) I will not so much as consider <hi rend="italic">the
               terms</hi>; I require the restitution of my own goods without <hi rend="italic">any
               terms</hi>. And I know you would do so were it your case. And so would any man of
            common sense. &apos;But she will not restore them.&apos; Then she must keep them. But
            let her not blame <hi rend="italic">me</hi> because I cannot trust her.</p>
         <p>Permit me to add one word to <hi rend="italic">you</hi>. You think yourself a match for
            her, but you are not. By her exquisite art she has already made you think ill of two
            very deserving women.<note place="foot" n="1"><persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers1793.xml"/>Sarah Ryan</persName> and <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers0506.xml"/>Sarah Crosby</persName>.</note> And you have
            been more than once much puzzled what to think of me! Nor could you help thinking me <hi
               rend="italic">a little</hi> in the wrong. I am almost afraid she likewise entertains
            you with the faults of many in the society, the knowing of which (be they real or
            feigned) does you no good at all. O sir, let us look inward, let us <hi rend="italic"
               >live at home</hi>! The more we know of our own faults and the less of other
            people&apos;s, the more will the work of God prosper in our hearts.</p>
         <closer>Wishing all happiness to you and yours, I am, dear sir,<lb/>
            <signed>Your affectionate servant,<lb/><persName>John
            Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
